Ralisti <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/udaedelousrector.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daedelous Rector</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dialated Rectum</span><br>  Posts: 285<br> <font color=#333333>(5/16/02 10:01:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=502.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Blasphemers</span><hr size=1> Obviously everyone disagreeing with this is too chicken to post something here, so I will.  It sounds a bit like an essay.  I hope you can bear with me.<br>
<br>
It is very easy to, with an open mind, conceive of religion as fake.  After all, there is no proof.  What you see from your point of view is a mass of people being led astray because of their emotional need for an outside deity.  They need something/someone that they can turn to for help.  Somewhere they can go when everything else has gone wrong.  A fake place, created by humanity for the sole purpose of making ourselves feel better.<br>
<br>
Then there is the flip-side.  After all, do you think you are one of the few elite to come up with this notion?  I would be hard-pressed to find someone who hasn't ever thought these things about religion...even his own.  <br>
<br>
You see, the problem is when you go deeper.  Instead of looking at the machine from the outside, you must delve into the depths of religion to see what really drives it forward...<br>
<br>
I cannot prove that religion exists, but I can assure you that people are not as naive as you think they are.  They base their opinions on very personal moments they have had.  There is not a moment in someone's life where they feel hopeless and idiotic and spontaneously decide to believe in God because they need someone to lean on.  Society has made humanity into a very questioning populace, and we are generally not led-astray easily.  <br>
<br>
My point is, the whole reason for the existance of fake-religions doesn't really hold up because it approaches the issue through the front door.  Instead, you must consider the issue from a differnt perspective.  The idea of an omnicient being existing must be conceived not by reading a Bible or Koran, but by actually taking part in a religion and feeling how it effects those it ministers to.  Evidence of something unprovable can only be found in the effects on the environment around it, just like the neutrino in particle physics.  It cannot be seen, yet most believe it exists because of the effects of it passing through bubble chambers.  It is the same with religion.<br>
<br>
I will not lie, though.  There are many people who could take religion in as a mere pill; something to go to when they feel ill.  And there are also those people who, as you said, grew up to believe it.  But eventually we are all confronted by the obvious notion that religion does not make a whole lot of sense.  It cannot be proved.  In fact, it is easy, as has been done here, to find a reason for it to be fake.  But I assure you that, when that time of questioning comes, everyone chooses their own path concerning religion with a high amount of predjudice, fear, and paranoia as you have here and, unless they are a complete fool, you will find that they have their own very good reason for believing what they do, and it is not what you think. <p><IMG SRC=http://daedelous.homestead.com/files/sigpic2.jpg>
</br>
<font size=-3><b>Daedelous "The Rectum" Rector/Deadsmith/Sweetsong/Burrolover, Hierophant</b>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uuggmopho.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uggmo Pho</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NT Action Hero </span><br>  Posts: 1985<br> <font color=#333333>(5/16/02 10:16:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=502.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.san.rr.com/monkboy/CaliNorml.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Religion</span><hr size=1> Yep they have their own reason and you said it...<br>
<br>
FEAR<br>
<br>
Fear of the unknown. Fear of death. Fear of something or nothing after death.<br>
<br>
I have no doubt that people have &quot;experiences&quot; that make them feel this way or that way about what they believe is real. <br>
<br>
But to take some &quot;feeling&quot; you have, wrap a whole bunch of bullshit around it, call it a religion and then SELL it to people (yes sell, tithing, offerings, etc etc) is crap.<br>
<br>
I'm alive, aware and thinking and I can tell you for a fact that I don't have the slightest clue what's gonna happen when I die. <br>
<br>
But some joker can come up to me and tell me they KNOW what's going to happen to me? They don't know SHIT. They know what some other fool told them, they know what they read in a book, i.e. they know exactly JACK and SQUAT.<br>
<br>
I have been reading about religion, mysticism, spirituality, aliens, etc etc etc for 33 years and there isn't a single jerkwater KNOWS anything. They can make a guess, they can have a method, they can try this or that but they DON'T KNOW ANYTHING BECAUSE NOBODY KNOWS.<br>
<br>
That's my problem with religion... marketing. If you have some groovy experience that makes you feel some strong power, force, trip, idea or whatever that is GREAT. Feel it, flow with it, do your thing but take it for what it is... PERSONAL. You don't know the answer for anyone else, you arn't inside anyone elses head and you sure as fuck arn't qualifed to decide what the hell I should be thinking, feeling and doing with regard to spirituality or whatever.<br>
<br>
Religion makes they claim that they KNOW.<br>
<br>
It is my opinion that is bullshit and anything that comes after that initial claim is not to be accepted or trusted.<br>
<br>
